******
[4] Addressing rumors in Saudi Arabia
Date: Sat 17 May 2014
Source: Hadth.org (Saudi Arabia) [in Arabic, machine trans., edited]
http://www.hadth.org/?p=4401577


Dates do not transmit the coronavirus; no cure for the virus
------------------------------------------------------------
In a statement from an expert to "Al-Riyadh" daily, she addressed rumors circulating in the social media about the coronavirus, its mode of transmission and treatment of patients. She particularly related to the rumors about the possible transmission of the "coronavirus syndrome" (Middle East respiratory syndrome CoV) by means of dates, and camel milk and camel meat. Plants can be contaminated, but only cells of mammalian animals and humans can be infected by the virus. There are no scientific studies to prove the opposite. The rumors about the possible role of dates are, according to the expert, exaggerated if not untrue; anyway, consumers are advised to wash dates.

Camel meat should be thoroughly cooked and camel milk boiled before consumption. Additional advice includes hygienic procedures such as cleanliness of kitchen utensils, use of gloves, hand washing, etc.

In reference to the propagation and trade in popular/folk medicaments, the expert advised people to ignore the mixtures and herbs promoted as treatment of MERS-CoV patients, which are misleading.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The social-media propagated rumors on the possible role of (mechanically contaminated) dates in the epidemiology of MERS-CoV is probably related to the suspected involvement of fruit bats. This route deserves to be scientifically checked in order to be decisively refuted or otherwise. - Mod.AS]

******
[5] Public response, Saudi Arabia

Date: Sat, 17 May 2014
Source: Daily Tribune [edited]
http://dt.bh/kissing-camels-is-it-safe/


The Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS) is very scary. This week, while avoiding the term global health emergency, the World Health Organisation (WHO) announced that the deadly viral infection was both serious and urgent, reported The Washington Post.

So far, there have been 571 confirmed cases of MERS; 171 of those people died from the disease.

There's one place, however, where the mood about MERS isn't scaring everyone. It's also the place where the infection was 1st reported in 2012 and where almost 500 recorded cases have been found so far: Saudi Arabia.

And the skepticism about the virus has taken a strange turn in Saudi Arabia, where people have begun kissing camels in response to MERS.

It seems a strange protest, but there's something behind it. Earlier this week, the Saudi government began a campaign to stop people from eating raw camel meat and liver or drinking unpasteurised camel milk.

Partly due to this fondness for camels, and partly due to a perceived lack of transparency from the Saudi government about MERS, a lot of people aren't totally convinced by the warnings about camels.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The world's camel population is estimated at about 25 million animals, most of them dromedaries (single-humped). The following statistics, derived from OIE's database, pertain to the 4 countries addressed above:

Ethiopia (2012): 2 245 581
Nigeria (2012): 92 699
Saudi Arabia (2012): 213 320
Tunisia (2013): 80 000

The information on the epidemiology of MERS-CoV, in particular concerning the virus reservoir and its transmission into the human population, has been considerably broadened since late 2013; item 1 is illustrative. It is indeed relieving to note the increased and energetic involvement of globally leading research institutions. However, there is still a long way to go; the picture is still rather hazy, as highlighted in items 2 and 3. This leaves room for rumors and unfounded perceptions within the threatened population, as demonstrated in items 4 and 5. Public education needs solid facts to become effective. Close cooperation between public health and animal health authorities, both on the national and international levels, is of paramount importance.

A regional technical consultation meeting on MERS-CoV is being arranged by the FAO, in consultation with its global and regional partners, in Muscat, Oman on 20 and 21 May 2014 with the participation of the main stakeholders from the region.

The main objectives of this meeting are to:
- review current knowledge on the disease in affected countries and the potential role of animal species in the epidemiological cycle of MERS-CoV;
- analyse the recent developments in diagnostic and surveillance tools to support animal investigations;
- identify and agree on actions that will minimize disease spread, based on current epidemiological knowledge; and
- discuss and agree on mechanisms for intra-regional cooperation in investigations, research and knowledge sharing.

The main expected outcomes of the meeting will be a better understanding of MERS-CoV overall, and in particular of the link between MERS-CoV and animal species, as well as the establishment of coordinated initiatives among countries for the effective monitoring of MERS-CoV in animal species.

See also FAO's review of 6 May 2014 at http://www.fao.org/ag/againfo/programmes/en/empres/news_060514.html.

OIE has updated its MERS-CoV Q&A page on 12 May 2014. The following excerpt, newly included in the page, is copied for the convenience of subscribers: "Though some camel infections with MERS-CoV have been associated with mild respiratory symptoms in the animals, current evidence does not indicate that MERS-CoV causes significant illness in camels. Evidence from the limited number of infections that have been identified also suggests that infection in these camels has been self-limiting. To develop a more complete understanding of the potential role of camels (and other animals) in the epidemiology of MERS, several types of investigation are needed:
1. Epidemiological studies which aim to determine the risk factors and potential exposure sources for camel infection and how camel infections relate to human cases of MERS; this includes genetic analyses of MERS-CoV.
2. Animal infection studies (including experimental challenges) to determine the behavior of MERS-CoV in camels (and other animals) and how the virus may be shed from infected camels.
3. In parallel diagnostic tests used for MERS-CoV surveillance in camels (and other animals) should be assessed for the reliability of their results in these species."

The need for experimental infection trials in camels has been addressed in ProMED-mail postings 20130811.1875301 and 20130907.1929762. The revised OIE Q&A is available at http://www.oie.int/en/for-the-media/press-releases/detail/article/update-may-2014-questions-answers-on-middle-east-respiratory-syndrome-coronavirus-mers-cov/. - Mod.AS]
